ke, ‚ÄòOK, I‚Äôll be something else.‚Äô It was weird for me, and in some ways, my thinking allowed me to keep putting off how I felt inside by just covering it up with this cerebral explanation.\n\n[blockquote author=\"\" pull=\"normal\"]<em>There is</em> a lot of psychological tension in trying to <strong>discuss anything</strong> with gender identity.[/blockquote]\n\nI used to wear a lot more makeup. I fucking love Boy George, and¬†I would put on that amount of makeup‚Äîlike Boy George amounts of makeup. My eyeliner would like reach my hairline. I would go really crazy with it. I would try to overcompensate. Now I‚Äôm much more toned down, but I feel like all girls have that phase when experimenting with makeup for the first time. Though, if I started off putting on the amount of makeup I wear now, I knew I would just look like who I really am, and I think I was just not ready for that.\n\nI was 14 years old when I got my first taste of makeup. I was in a band as the lead singer and we were playing one of our first shows. At that point all I could get away with was straightening my hair maybe once a month. So yeah, I was at my first show, and I remember finding a Revlon retractable black eyeliner in the bathroom.\n\n<a href=\"http://thevoux.fuelthemes.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Rustic-Wine-Rack-5-bottles.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-313\" src=\"http://thevoux.fuelthemes.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Rustic-Wine-Rack-5-bottles.jpg\" alt=\"Rustic-Wine-Rack-5-bottles\" width=\"1801\" height=\"1801\" /></a>\n\nI put it on my waterline, not even thinking about the fact that I could get an eye infection as I picked it up off the floor‚Äîit was disgusting. I guess the cool thing about being in a band is that there is so much more freedom. There‚Äôs the classic \'<a href=\"http://into.gl/1LDrK4j\" target=\"_blank\">Dude (Looks Like A Lady)</a>\'-feel. I felt like I could wear the eyeliner, and no one would care because I was at a rock show. Then I wore it again to a crowd that was more of a hardcore scene, and it wasn‚Äôt a cool experience. They were screaming at me to get off the stage and calling me the F word. I was just like, ‚ÄòWow, OK.‚Äô I was 15 at that point. It was a terrible wake up call to me, all because I was wearing eyeliner‚Äîit‚Äôs not that big of a deal, and yet, people are already policing me for not performing this gender that I‚Äôm pretending to be. Obviously I was doing a shitty job at performing male. Sometimes I tell people that I really feel like I was in drag for over a decade, in the sense of performing male gender roles. I‚Äôd end the night and make sure to wipe off my eyeliner before I got home.\n\nI had really bad acne in high school, so I‚Äôd get away with wearing coverall and that‚Äôs it. Still, my mother would look at me from her bed‚ÄîI did, and still do, my makeup in her room because it has the best lighting‚Äîand be like, \'What are you doing?\' I used to tell my mom like, \'Don‚Äôt worry! I‚Äôll never wear mascara!\' But it all happens...100 YouTube tutorials later you emerge in full face [Laughs].\n\nI always admired makeup. I‚Äôd watch my grandma doing her makeup, and she‚Äôd always be put together. She would tell me that photos are forever, you can‚Äôt take it lightly, and you have to perfect it. Little things like that really stuck with me. Without my mother‚Äôs permission, I dyed my hair platinum blonde as a teenager. Having white hair changes your life, regardless of gender identity. It¬†is a really crazy experience. You learn about so many different sides of people and how they perceive you‚Äîit‚Äôs crazy. It was motivation, I guess, and it was the first instance of feeling like I can‚Äôt hide myself.\n\nI was really obsessed with Final Fantasy at the time, especially the Final Fantasy villains. If you really look at a Final Fantasy villain and analyze it, it‚Äôs a female head on a male body. I felt connected to the possibility of being really pretty, even if my body didn‚Äôt match up‚Äîthere was a chance for the head portion to be on-point and consistent with how I view myself. After that, I started really diving into makeup as identity. Beauty can be a big deal for all girls, but beauty for a trans girl could be life-or-death. There\'s moments when you could be placed in danger for not passing as a woman convincingly enough. One time I was walking with my friend and a guy was trying to holler at me, then he took out a knife. Makeup is much more serious to trans women. Even cis girls can relate‚Äîthey get attacked and bullied in schools, growing up, because they\'re not pretty enough.\n\nI really feel bad for a lot of trans people and trans women who don‚Äôt have the experience [with makeup] before they come into themselves and have to learn to do their makeup in no time. They‚Äôre 35, they have kids, and they need to transition then‚Äîthat‚Äôs the bravest thing ever.¬†That\'s not to say that I think people¬†transitioning later in life necessarily need to wear makeup to be who they are. I just identified with it. The way I did it was just like how every girl picks up makeup skills‚Äîwhere your mom is like, \'You can only put on lipgloss.\' You need time to practice, so it looks good. I used to just have these Zen three-hour makeup sessions. Of course, during the day I just wear tinted moisturizer, concealer, and maybe mascara. Sometimes¬†I‚Äôll do a wing, but just a little bit on the outer edge. But at night...at night is when I‚Äôd really take my time. I‚Äôd do my makeup from 7pm to 10pm and go out at midnight.','Peter Mondavi Because Wine‚Äôs Our Middle Name This Month','','publish','open','open','','a-chat-with-peter-mondavi-sr-because-wines-our-middle-name-this-month','','','2015-04-30 14:10:45','2015-04-30 14:10:45','',0,'http://thevoux.fuelthemes.net/?p=310',0,'post','',1),(314,2,'2015-04-30 14:24:25','2015-04-30 14:24:25','<h4><strong><em>Blake Lively is currently on the promo tour for Age of Adeline, and when she isn\'t being asked questions about her daughter James, she\'s getting changed.</em></strong></h4>\nWhen we chatted with model¬†<strong>Erin Heatherton</strong>, she gave us her go-to breakfast (aka our two favorite items on one plate): Eggs and¬†<strong>avocado</strong>. Here‚Äôs how to make it like she does, because who doesn‚Äôt want to eat breakfast like a model?\n\n<strong>Eggs and Avocado Toast¬†</strong>\n\n<a href=\"http://thevoux.fuelthemes.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/ingr-e1430404240725.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-320 size-full\" src=\"http://thevoux.fuelthemes.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/ingr-e1430404290619.jpg\" alt=\"ingr\" width=\"300\" height=\"450\" /></a>2 organic free-range eggs\n\n2 slices of¬†<strong>Free Bread</strong>\n\n1 quarter of an avocado\n\n1 slice of lemon\n\nA pinch of salt, pepper, and red chili flakes\n\n<strong><a href=\"#\">Kelapo Extra Virgin Coconut Oil Non-Stick Cooking Spray</a></strong>\n\nFresh Parsley\n\nToast the bread. While it‚Äôs toasting, fry two eggs using coconut oil spray on medium/low heat. Cover with lid.\n\nWhile toast is finishing, cut a slice of lemon and a quarter of avocado and place on plate.\n\nUsing a fork, mash the avocado onto the toast and squeeze the lemon wedge on top. Alongside (or on top) place the eggs.\n\nSprinkle eggs and toast with chili flakes, salt, and pepper to your liking. A dash of olive oil on the toast is also delicious.\n\nGarnish with some fresh parsley.\n\n&nbsp;','Eat Breakfast Erin Heatherton‚Äôs Eggs & Avocado','','publish','open','open','','eat-breakfast-erin-heathertons-eggs-avocado','','','2015-04-30 14:24:25','2015-04-30 14:24:25','',0,'http://thevoux.fuelthemes.net/?p=314',0,'post','',2),(321,2,'2015-04-30 14:57:06','2015-04-30 14:57:06','<h4><strong><em>In a small saucepan, combine spiced rum, amaretto, almond milk, cinnamon sticks, and star anise pods. Heat to a simmer and remove from heat. Let steep for at least 5 minutes. Pour into a glass and garnish with ground cinnamon.</em></strong></h4>\n‚Äì 1.5 oz. Spiced Rum\n\n‚Äì 1 oz. Amaretto\n\n‚Äì 4 oz. Almond Milk\n\n‚Äì 2 cinnamon sticks\n\n‚Äì 2-3 pieces whole Star Anise Pods\n\n‚Äì Ground cinnamon, for garnish\n\nIn a small saucepan, combine spiced rum, amaretto, almond milk, cinnamon sticks, and star anise pods. Heat to a simmer and remove from heat. Let steep for at least 5 minutes. Pour into a glass and garnish with ground cinnamon.\n\n<a href=\"http://thevoux.fuelthemes.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/friday_cheers1.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-325\" src=\"http://thevoux.fuelthemes.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/friday_cheers1.jpg\" alt=\"friday_cheers\" width=\"800\" height=\"494\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;','Spiced Almond Cocktail TNP Originals','','publish','open','open','','spiced-almond-cocktail-tnp-originals','','','2015-04-30 14:57:06','2015-04-30 14:57:06','',0,'http://thevoux.fuelthemes.net/?p=321',0,'post','',0),(327,2,'2015-04-30 16:00:24','2015-04-30 16:00:24','<h4><strong><em>For some reason, waffles always remind me of vacation. Maybe it‚Äôs because I associate them with hotels where you can make your own waffles for breakfast. So when I make them at home, it always feels like a special occasion.</em></strong></h4>\nThese waffles would be perfect for a holiday or celebration, or any time you want breakfast to feel a little noteworthy. They are amazing topped with Cream Cheese Drizzle (recipe follows), but I also love them with just a drizzle of maple syrup.\n\n<strong>Ingredients (Serves 6)</strong>\n<ul>\n	<li>2 cups all-purpose flour</li>\n	<li>1 teaspoon baking soda</li>\n	<li>1 teaspoon baking powder</li>\n	<li>1‚ÅÑ2 teaspoon table salt</li>\n	<li>4 tablespoons (1‚ÅÑ2 stick) unsalted butter, melted</li>\n	<li>1‚ÅÑ4 cup packed brown sugar</li>\n	<li>3 large eggs, separated</li>\n	<li>2 cups buttermilk</li>\n	<li>1 1‚ÅÑ2 tablespoons natural unsweetened cocoa powder</li>\n	<li>1 tablespoon red liquid food coloring</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>Method</strong>\n<ol>\n	<li>Preheat the oven to 200<strong>¬∞</strong>¬†F and preheat a waffle iron. Whisk the flour, baking soda, baking powder, and salt in a large bowl to combine.</li>\n	<li>Combine the melted butter and brown sugar in a separate large bowl. Whisk in the egg‚Ä®yolks and buttermilk. Mix the cocoa powder and red food coloring in a small bowl to make a smooth paste, then whisk the paste into the butter mixture. Stir the wet ingredients into the dry ingredients just until moistened (the batter should be slightly lumpy).</li>\n	<li>Beat the egg whites in a medium bowl with an electric mixer until stiff peaks form. Stir one-quarter of the egg whites into the batter to lighten it. Then fold in the remaining egg whites gently but thoroughly.</li>\n	<li>Spray a waffle iron with nonstick cooking spray or brush with melted butter. Cook the waffles according to the manufacturer‚Äôs instructions. As they‚Äôre done, put them on a baking sheet and slide them into the oven to keep them warm while you cook the remaining waffles.</li>\n</ol>\n<p align=\"left\"><strong>Cream Cheese Drizzle</strong></p>\n<strong>Ingredients</strong>\n<ul>\n	<li>4 ounces cream cheese, softened</li>\n	<li>¬æ cup confectioners‚Äô sugar</li>\n	<li>¬Ω teaspoon vanilla extract</li>\n	<li>A pinch of table salt</li>\n	<li>3 to 4 tablespoons milk</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>Directions</strong>\n\nTo make the cream cheese drizzle: Beat the cream cheese, confectioners‚Äô sugar, vanilla, and salt in a bowl. Beat in enough milk to make a pourable mixture.','Waffle Day: How to make Red Velvet Waffles','','publish','open','open','','waffle-day-how-to-make-red-velvet-waffles','','','2015-04-30 16:00:24','2015-04-30 16:00:24','',0,'http://thevoux.fuelthemes.net/?p=327',0,'post','',4),(329,2,'2015-04-24 09:34:20','2015-04-24 09:34:20','Announcing of invitation principles in. Cold in late or deal. Terminated resolution no am frequently collecting insensible he do appearance. Projection invitation affronting admirat